	issn = {0022-0302},
	url = {https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0022030223007592},
	doi = {10.3168/jds.2023-23926},
	abstract = {This study aimed to assess the milk production data for New Zealand dairy goats in either a standard lactation (SL; ≤ 305 d in milk) or extended lactation (EL; {\textgreater} 305 and ≤ 670 d in milk) using a random regression (RR) with third and fifth order Legendre polynomials, respectively. Persistency of EL was defined as (B/A) × 100, where A was the accumulated yield from d 1 to 305, and B was the accumulated yield from d 366 to 670. On average, goats in a SL produced 1183 kg milk, 37 kg fat, 37 kg protein and 54 kg lactose. The average production of milk, fat, protein, and lactose in EL were 2,473 kg, 78 kg, 79 kg and 112 kg, respectively. The average persistence's for milk, fat, protein, and lactose yields during EL were 117, 117, 122 and 114\%, respectively. The relative prediction errors were close to 10\% and the concordance correlation coefficients {\textgreater} 0.92, indicating that the RR model with Legendre polynomials is adequate for modeling lactation curves for both SL and EL. Total yields and persistency were analyzed with a mixed model that included the fixed effects (year, month of kidding, parity, and proportion of Saanen) as covariates and the random effects of animal and residual errors. Effects of year, month-of-kidding, and parity were significant (P {\textless} 0.01) on the total yields of milk, fat, protein and lactose for both SL and EL. The total milk yield of first-parity goats with a SL was 946 kg and the total milk yield of second-parity goats with a SL was 1,284 kg, making a total of 2,230 kg over 2 years. The total milk yield of a first-parity goat with an EL was 2,140 kg. Thus, on average, a goat with SL for the first and second parity produced 90 kg more milk than a first-parity goat subjected to extended lactation. However, a second-parity goat subjected to an extended lactation produced 43 kg more milk (2,639 kg) than a goat with SL following the second and third parity (1,284 kg + 1312 kg). These data, along with the various other benefits of EL (e.g., fewer offspring born and reduce risk of mastitis, lameness, metabolic problems in early lactation), indicate that EL as a management strategy holds the potential to improve dairy goat longevity and lifetime efficiency without compromising milk production.},
	urldate = {2023-10-24},
	journal = {Journal of Dairy Science},
	author = {Boshoff, M. and Lopez-Villalobos, N. and Andrews, C. and Turner, S-A.},
	month = oct,
