	doi = {10.3389/fgene.2018.00318},
	abstract = {{\textless}p{\textgreater}Both natural and artificial selection are among the main driving forces shaping genetic variation across the genome of livestock species. Selection typically leaves signatures in the genome, which are often characterized by high genetic differentiation across breeds and/or a strong reduction in genetic diversity in regions associated with traits under intense selection pressure. In this study, we evaluated selection signatures and genomic inbreeding coefficients, {\textless}italic{\textgreater}F{\textless}/italic{\textgreater}$_{\textrm{ROH}}$, based on runs of homozygosity (ROH), in six Ugandan goat breeds: Boer ({\textless}italic{\textgreater}n{\textless}/italic{\textgreater} = 13), and the indigenous breeds Karamojong ({\textless}italic{\textgreater}n{\textless}/italic{\textgreater} = 15), Kigezi ({\textless}italic{\textgreater}n{\textless}/italic{\textgreater} = 29), Mubende ({\textless}italic{\textgreater}n{\textless}/italic{\textgreater} = 29), Small East African ({\textless}italic{\textgreater}n{\textless}/italic{\textgreater} = 29), and Sebei ({\textless}italic{\textgreater}n{\textless}/italic{\textgreater} = 29). After genotyping quality control, 45,294 autosomal single nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs) remained for further analyses. A total of 394 and 6 breed-specific putative selection signatures were identified across all breeds, based on marker-specific fixation index ({\textless}italic{\textgreater}F{\textless}/italic{\textgreater}$_{\textrm{ST}}$-values) and haplotype differentiation (hapFLK), respectively. These regions were enriched with genes involved in signaling pathways associated directly or indirectly with environmental adaptation, such as immune response (e.g., {\textless}italic{\textgreater}IL10RB{\textless}/italic{\textgreater} and {\textless}italic{\textgreater}IL23A{\textless}/italic{\textgreater}), growth and fatty acid composition (e.g., {\textless}italic{\textgreater}FGF9{\textless}/italic{\textgreater} and {\textless}italic{\textgreater}IGF1{\textless}/italic{\textgreater}), and thermo-tolerance (e.g., {\textless}italic{\textgreater}MTOR{\textless}/italic{\textgreater} and {\textless}italic{\textgreater}MAPK3{\textless}/italic{\textgreater}). The study revealed little overlap between breeds in genomic regions under selection and generally did not display the typical classic selection signatures as expected due to the complex nature of the traits. In the Boer breed, candidate genes associated with production traits, such as body size and growth (e.g., {\textless}italic{\textgreater}GJB2{\textless}/italic{\textgreater} and {\textless}italic{\textgreater}GJA3{\textless}/italic{\textgreater}) were also identified. Furthermore, analysis of ROH in indigenous goat breeds showed very low levels of genomic inbreeding (with the mean {\textless}italic{\textgreater}F{\textless}/italic{\textgreater}$_{\textrm{ROH}}$ per breed ranging from 0.8\% to 2.4\%), as compared to higher inbreeding in Boer (mean {\textless}italic{\textgreater}F{\textless}/italic{\textgreater}$_{\textrm{ROH}}$ = 13.8\%). Short ROH were more frequent than long ROH, except in Karamojong, providing insight in the developmental history of these goat breeds. This study provides insights into the effects of long-term selection in Boer and indigenous Ugandan goat breeds, which are relevant for implementation of breeding programs and conservation of genetic resources, as well as their sustainable use and management.{\textless}/p{\textgreater}},
